Hi,

we&#39;ve done this. Here are my experiences:

- have a driving force, e.g. you. Prepare to do legwork, convince people, 
and help them with JUnit
- get management/QA support. Not just superficial one, but prepare them to 
make tradeoffs when it comes to hard deadlines and still support you
- if possible, work ahead towards the hard questions: how can I get a 
persistent data setup? How to clean it up and make tests independent?
- start small, obviously, and incrementally build up your test base. If 
there are old tests, work with people to convert them to JUnit tests
- a big plus of JUnit is that you have single starting point to run all 
tests from, your root AllTests. That is a big selling point.
- embedd it into the dev process: noone releases anything without having 
running tests (of course it doesn&#39;t work fully, but you get the idea)
- have release engineering provide managers with feedback from daily builds 
and test runs about system quality state

At Skyva, I got a dedicated QA person to help implement JUnit support, but 
only after I had gone already an initial mile. Typically, QA is your 
friend. I hope QA in your place cooperates rather than fights development.

There is more, but I can&#39;t think of it right now.

Good luck,
Dirk



At 04:15 PM 3/16/2001 -0800, Kevin Bourrillion wrote:
&gt;Hi David,
&gt;
&gt;My preference would be to never grind development to a halt.  But, I would 
&gt;be aggressive about writing tests for all new development and all bug 
&gt;fixes.  Once your team is in this habit for a while you&#39;ll be well on your 
&gt;way.  Periodically you might use a code coverage tool to identify gaping 
&gt;holes in your testing and schedule a couple of person-days to plug them 
&gt;up.  Another way to prioritize new test development for old code is to ask 
&gt;yourselves &quot;what are we most concerned will break?&quot; and then test that.
&gt;
&gt;You&#39;ll never have a &quot;fully tested product&quot; -- I don&#39;t believe there is 
&gt;such a thing.  There will always be many more tests that could be there, 
&gt;no matter how many you write.  But, every well-conceived test helps a 
&gt;little more.
&gt;
&gt;Kevin
&gt;
&gt;
